and Judaism, for their part, also developed their own versions of formal education. Adherents of all three religions, and many others, celebrate formal education as one of these religions' greatest accomplishments. So how does religion become a reason not to attend any school at all? &#10;Moreover, the kind of extreme individualism evidenced by the family in this case is inconsistent with mainstream Christian thinking and practice. Christianity is a social religion. We worship together. We celebrate community. We help each other. If Christians don't want to have their children attend public schools, the alternative should be another school, not no school at all. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="974" language="en" documentId="271" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Jphubba" date="7/29/2013 6:27 PM GMT+0200" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/students-home-schooling-highlights-debate-over-va-religious-exemption-law/2013/07/28/ee2dbb1a-efbc-11e2-bed3-b9b6fe264871_comment.html?commentID=washingtonpost.com/ECHO/item/1375115278-973-22" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="271" notes="" title="Student’s home-schooling highlights debate over Va. religious exemption law"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="592"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="593" end="974"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43"/></xmi:XMI>